 the Clinton administration, especially in its relationship to America's intellectual and scholarly community. Barber also identifies the true faultlines of power that future candidates must negotiate if they are to win an election. For this edition, Barber has written a new afterword reflecting on Clinton's "vision" problem, his controversial role in shaping today's Democratic Party, and his efforts to confront the challenges of interdependence and terrorism. He concludes with a provocative assessment of Hillary Clinton as a Democratic primary candidate in the battle for the presidency.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aExecutive powerzUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aIntellectualszUnited StatesxHistoryx20th century. 0aIntellectualszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aPresidentsvIntellectual life. 0aPresidentszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aPresidentszUnited StatesvIntellectual life. 0aPresidentszUnited StatesxIntellectual life. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247240uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/barb1443840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231534864423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231534864/original  a978-3-11-044247-2  Columbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK